.SH NAME
sysopctl \- A custom Linux command for managing system resources and tasks.

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B sysopctl
[\fB--help\fR] [\fB--version\fR] \fIcommand\fR [\fIoptions\fR] [\fIarguments\fR]

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B sysopctl
is a system administration utility designed to manage system resources, services, processes, and overall system health. This tool provides a streamlined interface for performing common administrative tasks efficiently.

.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B service list
List all currently active services.

.TP
.B service start <service-name>
Start the specified service by name.

.TP
.B service stop <service-name>
Stop the specified service by name.

.TP
.B system load
Display the current system load averages.

.TP
.B disk usage
Show disk usage statistics for each partition.

.TP
.B process monitor
Monitor system processes in real-time.

.TP
.B logs analyze
Analyze recent critical log entries for troubleshooting.

.TP
.B backup <path>
Backup system files from the specified directory path.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B --help
Display help information for using sysopctl.

.TP
.B --version
Display the current version of sysopctl.

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B sysopctl service list
Lists all active system services.

.TP
.B sysopctl service start apache2
Starts the Apache2 service.

.TP
.B sysopctl service stop apache2
Stops the Apache2 service.

.TP
.B sysopctl system load
Displays the current load averages of the system.

.TP
.B sysopctl disk usage
Shows the disk usage statistics for all partitions.

.TP
.B sysopctl process monitor
Monitors system processes in real-time.

.TP
.B sysopctl logs analyze
Analyzes recent critical log entries for system health.

.TP
.B sysopctl backup /home/user
Backs up the contents of the /home/user directory.

